Sheet: Department Manager
Notes on Manager to Department Mapping
This layout is used to define which manager is responsible for which department. It serves as a quick reference or template for assigning departmental ownership.
ðŸ”¹ Purpose
To clearly map each manager to their corresponding department for organizational clarity, approvals, or access delegation.
ðŸ”¹ How It Works
Each row connects a Manager to a Department.
This structure ensures each department has a designated manager.
ðŸ”¹ What to Change
When reusing this layout:
Update manager names ("Manager 1", etc.) with actual names or titles (e.g., "Jane Doe").
Replace department names ("Department 1", etc.) with real departments (e.g., "Finance", "HR").

Sheet: Department OU
Notes on Department to OU Path Mapping
This layout links each department to its corresponding Organizational Unit (OU) path in Active Directory. Itâ€™s designed to help with user account creation.
ðŸ”¹ Purpose
To provide a clear reference for where each departmentâ€™s users should be placed in Active Directory.
ðŸ”¹ How It Works
Each Department is paired with a specific OU path.
The OU path indicates the exact location in AD where accounts for that department should reside.
ðŸ”¹ What to Change
When reusing this layout:
Update department names ("Department 1", etc.) to actual department names.
Adjust the OU path to match your real Active Directory structure:
Replace placeholder values like Domain, org, and Departments X with your actual domain and OU names.
Ensure the path reflects the correct nested OU structure (e.g., Departments under Users).

Sheet: Domain ( This sheet is used for the Termainated Staff script.
Notes on Domain and OU Configuration Layout
This layout defines the domain details and associated Organizational Unit (OU) paths used for managing user accounts in Active Directory across
environments.
ðŸ”¹ Purpose
To standardize the domain names, company identifier, and the OUs used for active and disabled users.
ðŸ”¹ How It Works
Domainorg / Domaincom: Represent different domain values in the Termainated Staff script.
Company: The name of the organization (used for identification or labeling).
EnabledOU: The OU path where active users are placed.
DisabledOU: The OU path where disabled or terminated user accounts are moved.
ðŸ”¹ What to Change
When adapting this layout:
Change the company name to reflect your organization.
Adjust OU paths to reflect your AD structure.

Sheet: Office OU
Notes on Office to OU Path Mapping
This layout is used to define which Organizational Unit (OU) path in Active Directory is associated with each office location. It's useful for managing
user accounts by physical location or branch.
ðŸ”¹ Purpose
To map office locations to their corresponding OUs in Active Directory, enabling location-based user provisioning and policy application.
ðŸ”¹ How It Works
Each Office is paired with an OUPath that reflects its organizational structure in AD.
The path follows a nested structure under Departments and Users.
ðŸ”¹ What to Change
When reusing this layout:
Update office names ("Office 1", etc.) to match real office or site names (e.g., "Chicago", "London").
Edit OU paths to reflect your actual AD hierarchy:
Replace placeholder values like Office X, Domain, and org with actual office names and domain details.
Ensure consistency with your AD structure.

